Linux kernel
============

There are several guides for kernel developers and users. These guides can
be rendered in a number of formats, like HTML and PDF. Please read
Documentation/admin-guide/README.rst first.

In order to build the documentation, use ``make htmldocs`` or
``make pdfdocs``.  The formatted documentation can also be read online at:

    https://www.kernel.org/doc/html/latest/

There are various text files in the Documentation/ subdirectory,
several of them using the Restructured Text markup notation.

Please read the Documentation/process/changes.rst file, as it contains the
requirements for building and running the kernel, and information about
the problems which may result by upgrading your kernel.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
userSpace:

1. cd userSpace

2. make clean

3. make

Create Mount Point (make sure it exists & has permissions):
4. sudo mkdir -p /mnt/memefs

5. sudo chmod 777 /mnt/memefs

Make sure memefs.img exists:
6. ls -l memefs.img

Mount MEMEfs:
7. ./memefs memefs.img /mnt/memefs -o debug

Testing:
Create new file:
8. echo "Hello!" > /mnt/memefs/testfile

Read file:
9. cat /mnt/memefs/testfile

Append to file:
10. echo "Appending" >> /mnt/memefs/testfile

11. cat /mnt/memefs/testfile

Delete file:
12. rm /mnt/memefs/testfile

13. ls /mnt/memefs

Check for errors:
14. dmesg | tail -n 20

Check for memory leaks w/ valgrind:
15. valgrind --leak-check=full ./memefs memefs.img /mnt/memefs -o debug

Unmount MEMEfs
16. sudo umount /mnt/memefs

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
kernalSpace:

1. Clean & Compile
make clean && make

2. Insert Module
sudo insmod memefs_kernal.ko

3. Make sure module is loaded
lsmod | grep memefs

4. Check Major Number
sudo dmesg | grep "Registered with major number"

5. Create Device File
sudo mknod /dev/memefs c 247 0
sudo chmod 666 /dev/memefs

6. Make sure device node is created
ls -l /dev/memefs

7. Create
echo "Creating a new file" > /dev/memefs

8. Write
echo "Appending data to the file" >> /dev/memefs

9. Read
cat /dev/memefs

10. Delete
sudo rm /dev/memefs

11. Remove device node
sudo rm /dev/memefs

12. Unload module
sudo rmmod memefs_kernel

13. Make sure it's unloaded
lsmod | grep memefs

14. Check logs
sudo dmesg | tail
